one may be related to the melting or dehydration of the oceanic crust which has been subducted with the underlying lithospheric plate. The ScS-to-P conversion interface inferred beneath southwestern Japan is more transitional than that beneath northeastern Japan. This difference in nature of the conversion interfaces must correspond to the difference in geological histories of both the regions. A high dip angle of the Philippine Sea plate in the Kyushu district and a low dip angle for the Shikoku district suggest that the normal-faulting subcrustal earthquakes beneath the Bungo channel and Iyonada, the western part of the Sevo Inland Sea, can be explained in terms of tearing and hinge faulting at the junction of the two slabs with different dip angles.},
