@misc{Giardini1988,
abstract = {The spectral splitting of the Earth's free oscillation eigenfrequencies$\backslash$ndeparts from that predicted on the basis of ellipticity and rotation$\backslash$nbecause of lateral heterogeneity in the structure of the Earth's$\backslash$nmantle and core and because of deviations from hydrostatic ellipticity$\backslash$nof the major internal discontinuities. For an isolated multiplet$\backslash$nof angular degree l, singlet eigenfrequencies and eigenfunctions$\backslash$nare fully determined by the coefficients cst of the splitting function$\backslash$n(s = 0,2,4,{\ldots}, 2l, −s ≤ t ≤ s). These coefficients constitute linear$\backslash$ncontraints on the Earth's heterogeneous structure of even spherical$\backslash$nharmonic degree s and order t; they are analogous, in this and other$\backslash$nrespects, to the spherical harmonic expansion coefficients of the$\backslash$nphase velocity distribution of a surface wave of given frequency.$\backslash$nFor an earthquake having known source parameters, knowledge of the$\backslash$nsplitting coefficients is also sufficient to predict, through a nonlinear$\backslash$nrelationship, the spectra of the multiplet at all stations. This$\backslash$npaper addresses the nonlinear inverse problem of estimating the splitting$\backslash$ncoefficients, cst , using, as data, observed spectra of the multiplet$\backslash$nfor an array of sources and receivers. The problem is solved by an$\backslash$niterative, least squares procedure in which the individual data are$\backslash$nthe complex spectral values obtained by Fourier transformation of$\backslash$nwindowed, long-period accelerograms from the International Deployment$\backslash$nof Accelerometers (IDA) network. Using recordings of large events$\backslash$nsince 1977, the data set consists of approximately 1000 narrow spectral$\backslash$nwindows, relating to 27 different modes, each spectral window containing$\backslash$none or two multiplets. The splitting function possesses a real part,$\backslash$nwhich is related to heterogeneity in density and elastic properties,$\backslash$nand an imaginary part corresponding to asphericity of anelastic parameters.$\backslash$nInversion is limited to the real and imaginary parts of the splitting$\backslash$nfunction for degree s = 0 and to the real part only for degrees s$\backslash$n= 2, 4. The complex c 00 term provides a very accurate determination$\backslash$nof the degenerate eigenfrequency and attenuation of the multiplet,$\backslash$nwhich constitute additional constraints on the spherically averaged$\backslash$nEarth. We find that splitting is systematically larger than that$\backslash$npredicted due to rotation and ellipticity. This phenomenon is particularly$\backslash$nevident for the PKIKP-equivalent modes (e.g., 13 S 2, 11 S 4) and$\backslash$nfor some very long period modes (3 S 2, 2 S 3) with significant sensitivity$\backslash$nin the inner core; it is also present, however, for modes sensitive$\backslash$nprimarily to mantle structure. Comparison between splitting functions$\backslash$nand the kernels characterizing their sensitivity with depth enables$\backslash$nus to identify large-scale patterns of heterogeneity in the Earth's$\backslash$nmantle and core. Forward modeling using existing heterogeneous mantle$\backslash$nmodels produces splitting functions in substantial agreement with$\backslash$nthose obtained from the modal observations if it is assumed that$\backslash$nvp and vs heterogeneity are proportional; it is necessary, however,$\backslash$nthat d In vs /d In vp has a value in the range 2 to 2.5 in the lower$\backslash$nmantle, a value much larger than is often supposed and roughly corresponding$\backslash$nto the case that lateral variations in shear modulus dominate those$\backslash$nin bulk modulus. Because the modal data are principally sensitive$\backslash$nto vS and the prior models of the lower mantle are based on short-period$\backslash$nP residuals, a